<font size="2" color="#990000"><b>INTERNATIONAL</b></font><br>




<font  face="times new roman"><b><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/22/international/asia/22KUND.html?todaysheadlines">Foreign Militants Seek Safe Passage From Afghan City</a></b><br>
Foreign militants trapped inside Kunduz have asked to leave Afghanistan through a protected corridor and travel to Pakistan.
<P>


<font  face="times new roman"><b><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/22/international/asia/22TALI.html?todaysheadlines">How bin Laden and Taliban Forged Jihad Ties</a></b><br>
Osama bin Laden's relationship with the Taliban helped lead the Afghan religious movement into a more global jihad and, eventually, doom.
<P>
</font>


<font  face="times new roman"><b><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/22/international/middleeast/22SAUD.html?todaysheadlines">Saudi Sees No bin Laden-Iraq Link</a></b><br>
Saudi Arabia's former intelligence chief said Wednesday that his government had seen no evidence that the Iraqi government had provided support to Al Qaeda.
<P>
</font>













<p>
<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/pages/world/index.html?todaysheadline">MORE INTERNATIONAL NEWS</a>
<br>

